a long-distance caregiving role, Olson finds her previous academic notions about assisting a frail parent increasingly at odds with the reality of the lived experience. In a narrative full of "ah-ha!" moments, tears, sighs, and outrage that will be familiar to many, Olson opens a window into the nursing home and home care industries that consume much in the way of taxpayer dollars, but often fail to deliver quality care. Olson's personal story vividly demonstrates not only the overwhelming bureaucratic barriers faced by care-dependent seniors but also their beleaguered adult children's attempts to ensure their parents' health, safety, and well-being.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aOlson, Laura Katz. 4aCultural Studies : Gerontology/Aging Studies. 4aGeneral Interest : General Interest. 4aHealth and Medicine : Health Care. 4aHealth and Medicine : Health and Society. 4aPublic Policy : Public Policy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gerontology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2016z978311149098440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143846075840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438460758423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438460758/original  a978-3-11-149098-4  SUNY Press eBook Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles